        <p>SUMMER RAIN By Marguerite Duras. Scribners, $18.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>SUMMER RAIN By Marguerite Duras. Scribners, $18.</p>
        <p>In 1984, Marguerite Duras made a film in Vitry, a "terrifying" suburb of Paris where many immigrants live. "Summer Rain," she tells us, is the result of unfinished business she left there -- a novel that presents the story of a troubled family and a boy, Ernesto, who refuses to go to school. Ms. Duras presents the battle between the unflinching school authorities and the somewhat mystical Ernesto through dialogue that seems reminiscent of the work of Samuel Beckett. However, Ms. Duras lacks Beckett's vision and his remarkable sense of humor. She means to tell us something about poverty, hopelessness and prejudice, but the style she has chosen (though ably translated by Barbara Bray) overpowers her.</p>
      </block>
